I'll start by executing the file_operations_reader tool to read the input data as the first step in the pipeline.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the data_processing_transformer requires data_processing_parser as a dependency, I'll first execute the parser to prepare the data for transformation.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now that the data is parsed, I'll proceed with the data transformation step using the data_processing_transformer tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Next, I'll execute the data_processing_filter tool to filter the transformed data as the next step in the pipeline.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now I'll proceed with the final step in the pipeline - data validation using the data_processing_validator tool. Since the validator requires a schema, I'll use a default schema for JSON validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
